<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-10-02T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-10-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="1587" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1587">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 819.001 P 82/3.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Chargé
                                    d’Affaires</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi>.</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Extract.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 220.]</seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Panama</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-10-02">
                                    <hi rend="italic">October 2, 1912</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to inform the Department
                            that the inauguration of Dr. Belisario Porras as President of the
                            Republic of Panama occurred yesterday in a dignified and orderly manner
                            and amid expressions of genuine enthusiasm upon the part of both the
                            number of those who were present at the National Theater at the
                            inaugural ceremony and by the populace assembled in large numbers on the
                            streets about the theater and the Presidential Palace.</p>
                        <p>The inaugural address contained very friendly and appreciative references
                            to the United States.</p>
                        <p>I have [etc.],</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Wm. Whiting Andrews.</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>